The one thing I still want you to tighten (best-practice “GOOD”)

Even with auth enforced, this part is still not ideal:

“Edge function accepts X-GitHub-Token header and forwards it.”

It’s not automatically insecure, but it’s not “best” because it keeps the GitHub token living on the client and being shuttled around.

Better (gold standard) pattern

Don’t pass the GitHub token from the browser at all.

User signs in via Supabase GitHub provider

Your backend (edge function) reads the GitHub token from the Supabase session server-side (or stores it once, encrypted)

All GitHub API calls happen from edge functions using that stored token

This prevents token leakage via:

browser devtools / extensions

accidental logs

client bugs that forward headers to the wrong place

Quick security checklist (to confirm you didn’t sacrifice anything)
A) Edge Function auth

✅ verify_jwt: true (or equivalent manual JWT validation inside the function)

✅ Requires Authorization: Bearer <supabase_access_token> (standard)
Avoid custom auth headers for identity.

B) GitHub token handling

Best → Good → Okay:

Best: stored encrypted server-side in Supabase + used only server-side

Good: fetched server-side via Supabase session provider token and never sent to client

Okay (your current): client sends token via X-GitHub-Token but only over HTTPS + no logs + no storage

If you stay on “Okay” temporarily, at least ensure:

function never logs request headers

GitHub token never appears in client error messages

C) Scopes (don’t overgrant)

For repo browsing + single-file commits, keep it tight:

repo (private repos) is broad; if you can, start with public repos first (public_repo) and upgrade later.

Avoid admin scopes unless truly needed.

D) CORS + rate limiting

Lock CORS to your domains only (dev + prod)

Add basic rate limit per user (or per JWT sub) so your proxy can’t be abused by a logged-in account

E) Storage (if you store GitHub tokens)

Encrypt at rest (Supabase vault / KMS-style approach, or application-level encryption)

Don’t put raw tokens in tables with loose RLS

